article.headline: Celts move ahead of New York and Miami
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Paul Pierce wasn't about to let the Boston Celtics lose. The game meant too much, coming as it did against a weak team at the end of a busy week. Pierce scored 13 of the Celtics' final 25 points, including solo 5-0 run that tied the score, to lead Boston back into playoff position with a 111-102 victory over the Washington Wizards on Saturday night. Pierce finished with 37 points and 12 rebounds in a victory broke a two-game losing streak and moved the Celtics from ninth to seventh place in the Eastern Conference, percentage points ahead of idle New York and Miami. "All non-playoff teams we must have. We must win games," Pierce said. "For sure, the Washington Wizards are a team that mathematically probably are not out of it, but that's a game we've got to have." The Celtics jammed five games into the week -- Sunday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday and Saturday -- and won three of them. The two losses came to two of the league's top teams, the Lakers and Pacers, and overall the Celtics have won seven of nine. "This is a test week for us to say: 'Hey, what are we going to do? Are we going to make the playoffs, or are we going to lay down the rest of the year?' And this was that week," Pierce said. "For us to go out here and get three out of five against some quality teams, it's a great feeling going into next week." Pierce had a jumper, a steal, a layup and a free throw in his five-point run that tied the score at 102 with 1:48 left. Ricky Davis then made a 15-footer to give Boston the lead, and Chucky Atkins' floater made it a four-point cushion with 46 seconds to play. Atkins finished with 17 points, and Davis scored 15. The Celtics finished the game with a 14-0 run over the final 3:45. Gilbert Arenas scored 28 and Etan Thomas added a career-high 21 for the Wizards, who lost their sixth straight. Jerry Stackhouse, playing his second game after missing six to rehabilitate his knee, scored 19 in 41 minutes. He has played in just 14 games all season. "I had a lot of opportunities to try to help win this game, and just didn't have it," said Stackhouse, who also played 41 minutes Friday against Atlanta. "Fatigue became a huge factor for me. I was in position to make plays that I usually make, and it wasn't there for me. I take full responsibility for this one, but I've got to get myself back into game shape," Stackhouse said. The Celtics took their first lead since the first quarter when Davis' steal at midcourt set up Walter McCarty's 3-pointer to make the score 95-94 with 6:10 remaining. But Thomas made two free throws to put the Wizards back in front with 4:54 to play, and he made it a five-point lead with a power move to cap an 8-0 run. Those were the last points Washington would score, but at least the Wizards didn't allow numbers of historic proportions for a change. They allowed Tracy McGrady to score 62 at Orlando on Wednesday, and five Hawks scored 20 or more in Friday's loss. The Celtics, meanwhile, improved to eight games under .500, hardly something to brag about -- unless it's good enough to make the playoffs. They now have three days of rest to watch the standings jumble themselves some more. "This has been the craziest year ever," Pierce said. "You're going to have two or three teams in the playoffs that are not even above .500. Hey, I'll take it regardless."

Game notes
Davis played despite spraining his left ankle in the fourth quarter of Friday's loss to Indiana. ... Washington's Kwame Brown started after missing Friday's game with a sprained left ankle, while Jarvis Hayes (pulled left hamstring) missed his third straight game. ... The Wizards are 1-17 against Atlantic Division teams. ... The Celtics have won four straight road games. ... Boston clinched the season series for the fifth time in six years. They lead 3-0 with one to play.
